It may be a Muslim?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when the Swiss voters have called for a ban on the construction of minarets and, in general, are spreading scare stories about alleged Islamization of Europe, John Bowen, an American academic, wrote and informed and thought about the fact that Muslims can integrate them - and whether - to one of the continent's secular society.
Some of the readers, after reading this book became admirers the artist's final work, " why the French do not like headscarves " (2006) , this elegant and discussed a study on the contentious issues that divide and employ the country for a period of 15 years and whose effects are still felt today.
Mr. Bowen's last book has a broader and more ambitious scope.
Like a good anthropologist wants to know not only what the politicians and the media said about Islam in France, but what actually happened in the base.
He spent months in mosques, schools and institutes, which are now taking care of 5 to 6 million French Muslims, which Mr Bowen called " Islamic ".
He is a good listener, reproduces the debate between teachers and students on the issues that are most worried about.
A Muslim Should enter into marriage in a mosque or a Hall (or both) ?
It should be taught by a young Muslim on the development and gay rights?
It may be a Muslim can marry a man who is not a Muslim?
Has the right to use areas of interest - based banking system, if it wants to get a mortgage?
It is these seemingly mundane issues, which are to be discussed, and which are part of everyday life, rather than the political dramas, which employ media.
Author identifies a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, among other well - known people, including the tarik Ramadan, Arab, Muslim scholar and academic, who was born in Switzerland.
This new generation is trying to open a debate on how you can simultaneously be a good Muslim and a good citizen in a modern secular society.
They have arguments for all their custom.
The Conservatives are suspicious of the actual idei French or European Islam.
Philosophers and activists with whom Mr. Bowen conducted interviews, tend to doměnce that is a counterpart Selafiho - supporters of Sunni Islam, combined in Saudi Arabia - this group is small, but also affects the European Muslims.
Mr Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism are compatible.
But the adaptation requires compromises on both sides.
It wonders how far the French politicians (and the intellectual elite, who doggedly defended the general public) is really committed to the idea of pluralism.
It is of the opinion that Muslims have in matters of faith are likely to experience less than Catholics, Protestants and Jews, who also had to make historic compromise with the secular republikánstvím.
Rather than the development of pragmatism found " tightening the screws values. "
It may be a Muslim? after reading this book, anyone can have a tendency to say " yes, but not now. "
