Gates: Iran faces further sanctions
Secretary of Defense Robert M. Gates said Friday that the world powers will soon impose on Iran " significant additional penalties " because of a lack of involvement in the talks on its nuclear ambitions.
Gates, who spoke to a group of about 300 American troops in northern Iraq during a week - long trip to areas where there is conflict in Afghanistan and Iraq, the prospect of military action against the Islamic Republic
This is not a good choice for Iran, said in response to an inquiry by a soldier on the of the likely evolution.
One of the things that depend on me, is that if I learned anything from Iraq over the past six years, [it] is an inherent unpredictability in the war.
The Obama administration decided on a package of sanctions that could affect the iranian military and political elite, but Gates indicated that some of these sanctions could also affect the ordinary Iranians.
He said that " the package of incentives and barriers " would require " to persuade the iranian government to actually feel less safe with nuclear weapons, " because " the people will suffer from sanctions.
According to Friday's opinion, issued by the White House spokesman Robert Gibbs, the administration has engaged European leader in warning that Iran will be serious consequences if its nuclear program fails to comply fully with the UN nuclear safety and its supervisory body, the International Atomic Energy Agency.
Iran insists it wants to develop their expertise for peaceful purposes.
In talks in Geneva on October 1, he indicated that he wants to return to talks on reducing their nuclear program and agreed to provide a substantial part of its stocks of enriched uranium in return for urgently needed fuel for the reactor to carry out medical research.
The administration has planted in such an agreement as a way to build confidence between the two parties and to gain time for negotiations.
But since then, it seems, Iran withdraws from the interim agreements - in part because, says the expert, because leadership is irámské is divided about whether to commit the United States.
Frankly, if the Iranian obstinacy to the international community for some suggestions, which are actually agreed in early October, I think it brought the international community, including the Russians and Chinese together on the way that is not on the terminology of additional sanctions against the Iranians, said Gates.
President Obama has set for 31 December deadline for Iran to respond to the proposals before returning to the search for other options, including monitoring, which Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton once called " sanctions ".
In its opinion, issued in New York, iranian mission to the United Nations on Thursday condemned what he called " unfounded and unsubstantiated allegations " against some members of the Security Committee of the Iranian nuclear activities and said that he wants to continue talks with the United States and five other world powers " to achieve an adequate long - term solutions.
Gates, who returned to Washington last Friday, he met this morning with Iraqi Prime Minister Nouri al-Maliki, before he flew to the area of Kurdistan, rich in oil, to meet with troops in Kirkuku and Kurdish leaders in Irbilu.
There remains a high tension between the Kurds and the Iraqi Arab majority, in particular because of the border, property rights and the distribution of income.
Gtes urged both sides to reduce the potential for conflict to zabránlo delay U. S. plans to reduce the U. S. the number of American troops from 115000 to 50,000 by the end of August.
Gates also sought to dampen concerns about Kurdish persistent depression. Official U. S. site quoted Gates, he told the US Massoudu Barzáanímu, President kurdistánské regional governments: " We want to protect your security, prosperity, and within a united Iraq.
We do not want to leave you. "
In an ageing China, change course
Wang and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters, which read that " Mother Earth is too tired to fund more children " and " one child, " also means a grave also.
Then they got a lesson that when the official government in Shanghai, low birth rate and ageing of the population in their city, suddenly changed course in the summer and began to encourage young couples, their response was immediate and determined: never.
We have always spent all their time and energy to just one child.
We have nothing left for the second, says Wang, 31 years old, manager of human resources, which has 8měsíčního son.
More than 30 years of China's policy of having only one child has been introduced and thus created two generations only the notoriously boubelatých and zhýčkaných children, " little emperors ", threatening the country's population crisis.
The average fertility rate has fallen to 1.8 children per couple, compared to six before vpolitika vsoupila force, according to UN figures.
The distribution of the population, where the number of people aged 60 years and above, predicts that the population 16.7 percent of the population in 2020 to 31,1 percent in 2050. that's far above the overall average of around 20 percent.
The imbalance is more rich coastal cities with a population with higher education, such as for example, in Shanghai.
Last year, people aged 60 years and above were almost 22 percent of the population registered in Shanghai, while the birth rate was less than one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, director of the Shanghai municipal population and family planning Commission said, many couples have children, " to help reduce the proportion of an ageing population and the reduction of the workforce in the future. "
He says that it's about " be old, it does not mean to be rich - as in developed countries such as Japan or Sweden. "
The gradual
As has been inserted into the Constitution of the country in 1978, China's one - child policy is probably still the most controversial mandate, established under the rule of the Communist Party.
The pair, who violated the policy, face enormous fines - up to three times their annual salary in some areas - and discrimination at work.
China's official positions advocated policies that helped the country to prevent the use of natural resources, while human rights defenders were sentenced to enforce the policy.
In rural areas, some officials urged pregnant women in the second child to undergo abortions.
In addition, many couples have to undergo a sexist selective abortion, leading to an unnaturally high ratio of men to women.
In recent years, population officials were progressively less severe in its opinion on the one - child policy.
In 2004, as a general rule, letting výce exceptions - including city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities and in cases where a man and a woman were only child - and in 2007 to mitigate the diction of their passwords, the hard line.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the population research Institute of Beijing University, said that officials of the central government has previously debated the more radical changes, such as to enable couples to have two children if one of the partners was an only child.
In June, Shanghai became the first Chinese city, which launched an aggressive campaign to encourage more births.
Almost overnight, the posters urge parents to have only one child, and replaced with a copy thereof, describing in detail how it would be legitimate to have a second child and how to apply for a permit.
The city administration has sent officials to plan families and volunteers to meet with couples in their houses and vsouvali leaflets under the door.
It also promised to provide emotional and financial counseling for those who have decided to have more than one child.
The response was cool, said officials for planning families.
Zarmucující response
Although officials in a rural town near Shanghai experienced an increase in the interest of couples who would like to have a second child after the start of the campaign, most of the precincts were reported changes.
Urban district with a population of 115000, for example, still registered four to five cases per month.
Disappointed officials in Shanghai said that despite the campaign is the number of births in the city in 2010 was still expected to be only around 165,000 - slightly higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng, head of the Committee for family planning in Shanghai, said that financial considerations were likely the main reason why people do not want to have more children.
They want to provide the best first child, he said.
Yang Jiawei, 27 years old, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26 years old, she said she would like to have two children, and they were legally allowed to be.
But like many Chinese, who have only a lack of health and life insurance provided by the government.
Without dociální a safety net could be the choice of irresponsible.
People in the West consider the one child policy as bad as a matter of legal question, says Yang, a civil engineer, whose wife is in the seventh month of pregnancy in association with the first child.
Yes, we have been deprived of the chance to have more than one child.
But the problem is not only in politics.
It is about money.
Other couples show the psychological reasons for hesitation.
Wang, manager of human resources, says that they have only one child, because she also was an only child: " We were the focus of our families and all of us.
We were not used for the provision of care and, in fact, we did not want to take care of the other.
Chen Zijian, 42 years old, who have their own translation company, put it much nepokrytěji.
For dvoukariérové middle - class parents, who lowered birth rates, he said, be successful means to be selfish.
Today's 20 and 30 years growing up my parents as is seen in the first days číského experiment with capitalism, and do not want this kind of a living for himself, he says.
Just one child places enormous demands on time parents, he says.
The mother must sacrifice for at least two years of his social life.
Then there are issues propstoru - " you have to rebuild your apartment - and the strategy - " you must have a resume prepared when the child is 9 months for a good pre - school education.
Most of his friends, he wants to do with one child says Che, but not two.
We are the first generation with higher živitními standards, he says.
We do not want to make too many victims.
The UN group has outlined a plan to reduce emissions.
The UN - sponsored conference on climate change - and each other - again on Friday focused on the release of the document, which proposes an ambitious reduction of greenhouse gases over the next 40 years with industrialized nations, most of the burden in the immediate term.
The text, which can provide a basis for a final political agreement on the regulation of greenhouse gases, stresses the remaining obstacles as well as the way forward.
But it was important to see progress in the negotiations, which took place at the wrong time with more than 100 world leaders who come to Copenhagen next week.
The UN working group created an ad hoc, on the text indicates how much money rich countries should provide the poor to deal with global warming in the short term and long term.
A provides a full range of options for the key issues, including how to develop and manage the emerging economies in order to reduce their output of carbon and what should be the upper limit for the increase in global temperature, which political leaders will be able to tolerate.
This dodábá process a great deal of flexibility, says John Coequyt, Senior Washington Representative of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who suggested the document of the 180 pages of text for the meeting to focus on what a top official on the issue of climate change at the United Nations, Yvo de Boer, described as a " big picture ".
Outlines the contours of a possible agreement in which the industrial nations could be collectively to reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent compared with 1990 levels, while the main developing countries could reduce their emissions during this period to reduce to 15 to 30 percent.
Together, the countries to reduce emissions by 2050 between 50 and 95 percent.
The European Union on Friday to discuss his promise to provide 3.6 trillion U. S. dollars over the next three years to help the poorer countries to adapt to climate change - from managing floods and droughts to prevent deforestation.
Still, but on Friday said the same kind of verbal fireworks which prevailed at the talks in the last week.
U. S. Special envoy for climate change Todd Stern dismissed the speech, calling for mandatory restrictions on greenhouse gas emissions for industrialised countries compared with the main emerging economies, if not funded by the developed world.
The move signaled that the Obama administration raised a harder line towards China, get outta officials of the Bush administration just two years ago.
The United States accede to the treaty without the transfer of the major developing countries and the implementation of actions, " said Stern, who also complained that the text is not sufficient to cover the restrictions and should be examined by outside observers.
Stern made this comment about an hour after the Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei said the main U. S. negotiator on climate issues that either a lack of " common sense " or " exceptional " led to a week earlier in a statement that the United States would not help China to deal with global warming.
With the future of the world's major economic powers at stake, both within the developing world, and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current fighting is mostly on the conservation of individual economies, rather than on the conservation of the planet, between China and the United States on the implementation of their respective commitments, while poorer nations point to the fact that two of the most influential countries in the world to ignore the scientific imperative for the implementation of the action.
Ricardo Ulate, delegate of Costa Rica, said that it is not surprising that the major powers are fighting over who should bear the costs of reducing greenhouse gases while vulnerable countries have become much more aggressive in the search for a way to prevent the large issuers responsibly in their actions.
This is clearly a play about the fact that new economic hegemony is developing, he said, which also serves as a regional adviser on regional climate change in Mexico and Central America for international conservation.
Some of the countries that are most zranitelnelné the effects of climate change have indicated that they wish to continue to promote a legally binding agreement in Copenhagen, but most of the major parties, said that the best outcome of the talks will be the political agreement.
The alliance of small island states, which has 43 members, has created a draft agreement last Friday morning.
Artur Runge - Metzger, who led the international negotiations on climate change in favour of the European Commission, said that the enforcement of the small island nations, " the whole process polirtický " partly because they are now united and demand action from growing economies such as China and India
Negotiations led to a new urgency when the delegates focused on the fact that most of the remaining contentious issues must be resolved before the heads of government on the deal.
High - ranking officials, such as for example, the Indian Minister of environmental protection and the Chinese Deputy Minister of stepped out of the aircraft and ran through the halls Bella Center to the closed door meetings and conferences of the new chart so they could claim to be examined next week.
Total vastness Assembly - where 13,000 people a day move along on the convention center, and from the guitar playing activists staged at night ironic spectacle of the countries, which are believed to be sent, and there were proposals for the transfer from hand to hand on paper rather than by electronic mail - controlled by the challenge.
