The British first train with a speed of 140 miles per hour this Monday feelings
At 5:13 In on Monday morning whistle cut through the darkness as a sign of the departure of the train, which meant a revolution of transport in Britain.
The first high - speed passenger train in the country reaches a speed of 140 miles per hour and fly from Ashford in Kent to London St Pancras and the distance of 58 miles in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the Minister of Transport, then joined Kelly Holmes and got into the first high - speed passenger trains outside lLndýn.
He hopes that the new service, where appropriate, or join the Britain with an international network of fast, reliable trains, and joins a large agglomerations Midland, North and Scotland with London.
Neglected backwater should shorten transport times in passenger traffic and trade routes and the transition from aircraft and rail cars would reduce carbon emissions and eliminate congestion on the roads.
In theory, the three main political parties had left to get to this vision.
But dozens of bilinů pounds needed to build a new national railway network, the inevitable fight for projects and concerns about environmental insults now constrain the development of the British high - speed lines.
High Speed Two (HS2) , a company created in January to provide a government study, submitted its report to Lord Adonis December 30, as stated by the Times.
She gave him a detailed map of the routes of the next stage of the planned high speed network.
The new trace links London with the West was designed to five meters in urban areas and neighborhoods, where he would be on the propstředí could be problematic.
In the open country was scheduled to 25 m in the final route.
HS2 also expected to identify three broad options for high - speed network leading to the north.
Lord Adonis will reply in the spring.
The preferred option is konfikurace Y - shaped, with one high - speed line should lead to the West Midland.
The track should share with one near the Birmingham, passing through the branches, the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland and the other, leading to the northeast in Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle over the Tyne.
One track should lead to Scotland.
" It seems that it was the most effective choice, " he said, and a railway expert.
Once this is done, driving times between London and Edinburgh is reduced to two hours and 40 minutes.
The first stage, which will not be opened before the year 2025, could enable passengers to travel between London and Birmingham for 49 minutes, compared with more than one hour in the present.
Proposals should allow trains to run at a speed of 2 miles per hour, which would make the British network the fastest in Europe.
The initial route has been proposed so as to hold the trains in the length of 400 m, which would have been able to carry 1100 people.
Up To 18 sets could operate every hour on the route London - Birmingham.
This means that the London terminal would be able to serve, if necessary, to 20 000 passengers per hour.
Due to capital constraints, it is assumed that the existing station would be extended so as to include high - speed network.
Experts from železničníhoprůmyslu argues that only San Pancras International and Euston offer such potential.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not to implement this scheme, but a wide - ranging public consultation and planning procedures mean that the final decision will not be made before the general election.
Even if the wheels in motion, the network should be built in parts.
Trains should be first put into service on the high - speed lines, but the existing lines north of Birmingham and maintain the journey times between London and Scotland over three hours.
This is regarded as a critical point of contact for the transition from the aircraft to trains, a landmark for the revolution to rail.
